le</strong> and <strong>metron</strong> meaning <strong>measure</strong>. S=
o the word <strong>Trigonometry</strong> literally means: "Triangle measure=
ment", or perhaps a better way of putting it: "How to measure triangles"<br=
><br>Now take a look at what we have in the diagram above:<br>Sine, Cosine,=
 Tangent, Cotangent, Secant and Cosecant.<br><br>As I understand it, all th=
ese words were originally defined in terms of moving in an anti-clockwise d=
irection from the origin point of a curve, such that a 90 degree triangle i=
s formed, <strong>inside</strong> the curve.<br><br>This is why we draw our=
 triangles <strong>inside</strong> the unit circle.<br><br>Now, the word <s=
trong>Sine</strong> originates from the Latin word <strong>Sinus</strong>, =
and it means <strong>curve</strong> or <strong>bay</strong>. Here it is use=
d to mean: The line formed by the <strong>inside</strong> triangle, that is=
 closest to the curve.<br><br>The word <strong>Secant</strong>, is from the=
 Latin word <strong>secare</strong>, and it means <strong>to cut</strong>. =
