angle, that when extended, cuts the curve.<br><br>The word <strong>Tangent<=
/strong>, in Latin, means <strong>touching</strong>. Here it is used to mea=
n: The line that touches the curve, at the same point where the inside tria=
ngle touches the curve. This line also touches the <strong>secant</strong> =
line. But I don't know if that was part of the original meaning. It could a=
lso have meant: The line that touches the end-point of <strong>secant</stro=
ng>" and the point where the <strong>inside</strong> triangle touches the c=
urve. It works either way though.<br><br>Now take a look at the co-function=
s, they are, Cosine, Cosecant and Cotangent.<br><br>The "co-" prefix comes =
from Latin, it literally means "complimentary", or as I like to think of it=
: "at 90 degrees to something"<br><br>So you get:<br><br><strong>Cosine</st=
rong> for: The line complementary to the <strong>Sine</strong>. Or stated a=
nother way: The line at 90 degrees to the line of the triangle, closest to =
the curve.<br><br><strong>Cosecant</strong> for: The line complementary to =
the <strong>Secant</strong>. Or rather: The line at 90 degrees to <strong>S=
ecant</strong> that, when extended, also cuts the curve.<br><br><strong>Cot=
angent</strong> for: The line complementary to the <strong>Tangent</strong>=
. Or perhaps better understood as: The line-segment of the <strong>extended=
